### Overview
This document provides the specifications of the Castor EDC API, describing the currently available
API endpoints and methods. We aim to provide a fully functional RESTful API to communicate with
Castor EDC and these are endpoints currently available.

The formal OpenAPI 2 specification by which this page is rendered is also available in the following formats:
* [YAML](https://data.castoredc.com/api/swagger)
* [JSON](https://data.castoredc.com/api/swagger?format=json)
* [JSON (pretty print)](https://data.castoredc.com/api/swagger?format=json_pretty)

### Authentication & Authorization with OAuth 2
Authentication and authorization are arranged through OAuth2. We currently provide full support for the Client
Credentials flow. The Authorization Code flow is supported, but we ask you to contact us if you want to use this flow.

To use the Client Credentials flow go to your
[Castor EDC profile](https://castoredc.link/manual/api/application_programming_interface) and generate
a Client ID and Client Secret. Use the Client ID and Client Secret to retrieve an access token by making a request to
the '/oauth/token' endpoint with your client_id and client_secret as parameters and grant_type=client_credentials.

PHP Example:
```php
include __DIR__.'/vendor/autoload.php';
use Guzzle\Http\Client;

// Create the HTTP Client.
$httpClient = new Client(
    'https://data.castoredc.com',
    [
        'request.options' => [
            'exceptions' => false,
        ]
    ]
);

// Build the request
$request = $httpClient->post(
    '/oauth/token',
    null,
    [
        'client_id'     => 'YourCastorClientId',
        'client_secret' => 'YourCastorClientSecret',
        'grant_type'    => 'client_credentials',
    ]
);

// Send the request
$response     = $request->send();
$responseBody = $response->getBody(true);
$responseArr  = json_decode($responseBody, true);
$accessToken  = $responseArr['access_token'];
```

In your subsequent requests you can use the `$accessToken` as a Bearer token in the Authorization header, i.e:
```php
$request = $httpClient->get('/api/user');
$request->addHeader('Authorization', 'Bearer '. $accessToken);
$response = $request->send();
echo $response->getBody();
```

### OAuth2 Scopes

There are 3 scopes that endpoints may support.
 * **default**: allows access to all endpoints
 * **study_statistics**: allows access to study statistics
 * **record**: allows access to data for a single participant

Due to [a bug in the OpenAPI UI](https://github.com/swagger-api/swagger-ui/issues/5062), all three scopes are listed for all endpoints.

If the endpoint supports something other than the default scope, the summary will have a 🔭 emoji and the scope will be
listed in the description as well as under the `security:` key in the [specification](https://data.castoredc.com/api/swagger).

### Rate Limits
Unless specified in the resource, endpoints are rate-limited to 600 requests in 10 minutes.

